 MDGs, the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) were formed in 2016 with the intention of managing the issues fundamentally ignored by the MDGs. Drawing on twenty-five years of research on development goals, human rights, and the organizations that promote them, Nelson reasons that transformative change arises out of national and local movements, and shows how human rights can offer leverage and political support that help drive transformative national initiatives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHuman rights. 0aSustainable development. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Economic Development.2bisacsh  aMDGs.  aMillennium Development Goals.  aNGOs.  aSDGs.  aSustainable Development Goals.  aglobal South.  aglobal development.  ahuman rights.  ainequality.  ainternational development.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751261340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487512613423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487512613/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles